.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Code: \[la]https://github.com/sunaku/binman\[ra]
.IP \(bu 2
Docs: \[la]https://sunaku.github.io/binman/man\[ra]
.IP \(bu 2
Bugs: \[la]https://github.com/sunaku/binman/issues\[ra]
.RE
.TH binman \- manpages from header comments
.PP
binman generates manual pages from header comments in your scripts so that you
can keep your documentation and implementation together, in the same file, for
easy maintenance.  But keeping them apart, in separate files, is supported too.
.PP
[Obligatory screen\-shot of 
.BR binman (1) 
in action!](EXAMPLE.png)
.SH Features
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Direct support for any scripting language that has multi\-line comments or
uses \fB\fC#\fR for single\-line comments such as Ruby, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Tcl,
Node.js, Elixir, make, AWK, sed, UNIX shells, Windows PowerShell and more!
.IP \(bu 2
Individual commands for manual page extraction, conversion, and display.
.IP \(bu 2
Accessible from the command line and also as a library in Ruby \[la]https://www.ruby-lang.org/\[ra] scripts.
.IP \(bu 2
Implemented in roughly 165 statement lines (SLOC) of pure Ruby \[la]https://www.ruby-lang.org/\[ra] code! :\-)
.RE
.SH Examples
.PP
Here are some examples of HTML manual page \fIsets\fP generated by 
.BR binman-rake (1):
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\[la]https://sunaku.github.io/dasht/man\[ra]
.IP \(bu 2
\[la]https://sunaku.github.io/tork/man\[ra]
.IP \(bu 2
\[la]https://sunaku.github.io/binman/man\[ra]
.IP \(bu 2
\[la]https://sunaku.github.io/md2man/man\[ra]
.RE
.PP
For examples of input and output files, see "From the command line" below.
.SH Installation
.SS Requirements
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Ruby \[la]https://www.ruby-lang.org/\[ra] 1.8.7 or newer
.RE
.SS For users
.PP
If you only want to view pre\-built manual pages:
.PP
.RS
.nf
gem install binman
.fi
.RE
.PP
If you also want to build your own manual pages:
.PP
.RS
.nf
gem install md2man \-v '~> 5.0'
.fi
.RE
.SS For developers
.PP
.RS
.nf
git clone https://github.com/sunaku/binman
cd binman
bundle install
bundle exec binman \-\-help # run it directly
bundle exec rake \-\-tasks  # packaging tasks
.fi
.RE
.SH Usage
.PP
First, write 
.BR md2man (5) 
text for your script: either in a comment at the top of
your script file, as described under "Embedded manpage sources" in 
.BR binman (1),
or in a separate Markdown file located at \fB\fCman/man?/*.?.{markdown,mkd,md}\fR\&.
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
For real examples of what to write, see "From the command line" below.
.IP \(bu 2
For the detailed syntax and semantics of what to write, see 
.BR md2man (5).
.RE
.PP
Next, you have two ways of generating manual pages from what you've written:
.nr step0 0 1
.RS
.IP \n+[step0]
Generate manual pages at "compile time" and ship them with your scripts.
.IP \n+[step0]
Generate manual pages at "run time" so that your scripts are standalone.
.RE
.SS At compile time
.PP
Run 
.BR binman-rake (1) 
to generate manual pages for all of your \fB\fC\&./bin/*\fR scripts.
.PP
Alternatively, to have more control over the generation of your manual pages:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Run \fB\fCbinman text\fR to extract manual page text from a specified script.
.IP \(bu 2
Run \fB\fCbinman roff\fR to generate a UNIX manual page from a specified script.
.IP \(bu 2
Run \fB\fCbinman html\fR to generate a HTML manual page from a specified script.
.RE
.SS From the command line
.PP
Below are some real examples of generating manual pages from the command line.
Note that 
.BR binman-rake (1) 
abstracts away all of the complexity you see below!
.PP
.BR dasht (1):
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
